# Code Annotation for PR Readability

A reviewer should be able to scan a diff top-to-bottom and understand it without reverse-engineering the code. Annotate every meaningful segment with a brief, high-signal comment that states **intent** — what it does, and (when not obvious) why.

- **Annotate:** non-trivial functions, key branches/guards, data transforms, gates, schema/contract boundaries, fallbacks, and any non-obvious decision or trade-off. One line above the segment is usually enough.
- **Lead with intent, not syntax.**
- **Do not narrate obvious lines** — imports, simple assignments, plain getters, self-evident one-liners. Restating the code is noise and ages badly.
- A function-level comment plus a few in-body segment markers beats a comment on every line.

The comments are the table of contents for the diff.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — narrates syntax / no intent
// call update then create
try { await update(id, body); } catch { await create(body); }

// ✅ GOOD — states intent + the non-obvious why
// Template ids are stable, so try update first and fall back to create
// for a template the API hasn't seen yet.
try { await update(id, body); } catch { await create(body); }
```

```python
# ✅ GOOD — segment header explains the transform's purpose
# Text steps scale with tokens; use typical assumptions when a step
# doesn't declare its own estimate so the panel still shows a number.
tokens = step.get("estimatedTokens") or DEFAULT_STEP_TOKENS
```
